üó£Recently Washington Post has published interview with Kirill Budanov, chief of Ukrainian military intelligence. He repeated usual Ukrainian fairy tales for the Western audience, but there were some alarming statements as well.

Naturally, he didn‚Äôt miss an opportunity to show off to his Western masters telling a story how he personally forecasted the beginning of Russian SMO. He probably read too many Western media that have been regularly giving such hysterical forecasts since 2014 or even earlier. 

And then he just went out of control. It turned out that Russian advances in Donbass don‚Äôt matter, there will be no decisive offensive and Ukraine will return Crimea by summer. Oh, and no need to worry about Russia using nuclear weapons, it won‚Äôt happen even if Russian territorial integrity will be threatened. 

No comments. He repeats the same things that Zelensky & Co. have been telling us for a year ‚Äî we are winning, Russia is powerless, and so on. 

Budanov had fallen to even greater debts stating that Vladimir Putin is terminally ill for a very long time. It was Budanov who advised Zelensky to play ‚ÄúPutin is not real‚Äù card in Davos. A chief of intelligence worthy of a clown playing president. 

Of course, he couldn‚Äôt forget traditional ‚ÄúRussia is out of missiles‚Äù. Looks like Russia is out of missiles every month since the very beginning of SMO. Ironically, his statement came just a day after another massive strike against military facilities of Kiev junta. 

However, one of Budanov‚Äôs statements deserves attention ‚Äî he says that his service is active on Russian territory recruiting people and preparing acts of sabotage and terrorist attacks.

Unfortunately, this possibility can‚Äôt be ruled out. Ukrainian special services are very active in Russian Internet and we often hear of them recruiting some of not so bright young men or even schoolchildren. 

They are acting not only at new Russian territories but over the entire territory of Russia. Russian counterintelligence works against them but sometimes the enemy is still able to find potential terrorists. 

The enemy uses the same scheme as drug dealers ‚Äî secret channels, good money for ‚Äúsimple work‚Äù, no personal contact, etc. It‚Äôs hard to counter such tactics, so it is necessary to inform schools, colleges and universities about it to reduce the risks. 

However, recruited idiots are not the most serious threat. Russia has already suffered several serious terrorist attacks and it will be na√Øve to think that the enemy isn‚Äôt trying to repeat them. 

As Zelensky and other junta members continuously announce their plans to capture Crimea, this region may remain one of the main targets for Ukrainian terrorists. As Russian Armed Forces successfully advance, the danger of terrorist attacks increases. So, Russian special services have to stay on alert and don‚Äôt forget Crimean bridge lessons.
Who was working in concentration camps during WWII as guards and tormentors?

üí¨ 79 years ago, on January 27th, 1944, Leningrad was fully liberated from the Nazi military blockade that lasted almost 900 days and was one of the harshest trials for the Soviet people.

The siege of Leningrad commenced on 8 September 1941. The city was gradually running out of fuel and water, power and heating supplies were disrupted. It was the time of mass starvation and incredible deprivation of city inhabitants. Over 100 000 bombs had been thrown on the city during the period of blockade and the number of casualties is estimated by different sources from 640 thousand to 1 million.

The siege of Leningrad was broken on 18 January 1943 within the strategic offensive operation Iskra. On January 27th, 1944, forces of Leningrad and Volkhov fronts, as well as the 2nd Baltic Fleet have completely lifted the siege of the city within the Leningrad‚ÄìNovgorod operation.

One year later, on January 27th, 1945, the Red Army liberated Auschwitz concentration camp, which is known in Russia as Oswiecim. It was the largest of the German Nazi concentration camps and extermination centers. Over 1.1 million men, women and children have lost their lives here.

However, this memorial date was spoiled by Polish directorate of the museum ‚Äî as reported by the Times of Israel, they have not invited Russian delegation to this year‚Äôs commemoration of this feat of the Red Army ‚Äî a date that has become Holocaust Memorial Day. 

Until now, Russia has always taken part in the commemoration held every year on January 27, with its delegate speaking at the main ceremony. Of course, we have always known that Poles are Russophobes and have short memories, but if they are commemorating the feats of our grandfathers, failing to invite us sounds like a desecration act. 

Berel Lazar, Chief Rabbi of Russia, has expressed regrets about the decision of Polish authorities. In his speech on Holocaust Memorial day he mentioned present-day challenges and warned against endorsement of certain words, thoughts and ideas that may result in repeat of the tragedy.

Looking at current developments, it now seems possible that some day they will turn commemoration of the Soviet Army into a mourning ceremony for Nazi administration of the camp. Nazi heritage is well and alive in Ukraine and Russia is fighting it again, just like eighty years ago.

Polish people should better rethink their history. Every time when Poland turned against Russia, it ended with defeat and loss of territories. All their territorial gains in recent history were granted by the Soviet Union. Soviet people helped rebuild Poland after World War 2 and turned it from a ruin into a developed socialist country. 

Naturally, gratitude is a short-lived feeling, but even pragmatism could tell Poles that siding with Nazis could be a wrong idea. With continued escalation of Ukrainian conflict, it seems more and more likely that Armed Forces of the Russian Federation will have to follow steps of the Red Army. Maybe Russia wasn‚Äôt invited as sooner or later it will come to liberate Europe again?

‚ö°Ô∏èRussian Representative at UN Security Council says that special military operation can be ended only when Ukraine will no longer pose a threat for Russia and will not discriminate Russian speakers. 

SMO can be ended only when there will be no threat to Russia from territory of Ukraine and there will be no discrimination of Russian-speaking population of the country. If this result can be achieved through negotiations, we are ready for this scenario. If not, all objectives will be achieved with military means. Neither Kiev regime nor its Western sponsors have learned necessary lessons from Ukrainian events.

This statement is yet another reiteration of Russian objectives. It notably does not specify territorial issues, so we can assume that liberation of the entire territory of four Russian regions is not a subject to discussion.

As for the rest, this official statement is notable as it gives more specific definition of denazification. Western media and politicians usually dismiss Russian objective of denazification stating that ‚Äúthere are no nazis in Ukraine that has a Jewish president‚Äù. They care about words and not about their meaning and they are firmly on Ukrainian side, so as long as Ukraine does not call itself ‚Äúnazi‚Äù, they will deny it.  

Of course, they all understand the realities of Ukraine, but if it is just about calling Nazism ‚Äúdiscrimination of Russian-speaking population of the country‚Äù, we can play along. If our former ‚Äúpartners‚Äù need everything explained in simple terms, Russia can do it.

Unfortunately, international forums have proven to be useless with regard to resolution of Ukrainian conflict. These institutions have been dominated by the West for a long time and are absolutely impotent when it comes to negotiations between the parties.

UN structures are under continuous pressure from the U.S. to take the side of Ukraine in the conflict and distort data in favor of Ukraine. This works, especially since most UN officials come from the West and its satellite countries. Lack of impartial coverage and assessment results in extension of Ukrainian conflict.

Russia keeps trying to promote its view in UN and it works to a certain extent, if we look at statistics of recent vote about condemnation of Nazism. By the way, Western countries that have all voted for glorification of Nazism actually understand that Russian denazification objective has all valid reasons. 

And yes, this also means that not just Ukraine needs denazification. Because Nazism is not only about concentration camps and gas chambers. Nazism is a manifestation of the idea of ethnic superiority, which is obvious in Ukraine. 

Western countries and especially the US do feel superior to other nations. They feel that their ideology is superior, they feel that their values are the only right values and aim to promote it. Moreover, they are not hesitating to use force for this purpose, when they feel they won‚Äôt meet resistance. 

While not Nazism in classical sense, neoliberal globalism is yet another threat to humanity. The West has to accept new realities or ‚Äúdeglobalization‚Äù will become the next primary objective of free world.

‚ùóÔ∏èAmerican journalist Deborah Armstrong known for her objective coverage of human rights violations in Donbass by Ukrainian government, support of Faina Savenkova and crusade against the infamous Mirotvorets website, has reported a first success ‚Äì  UNICEF appears to have finally taken the additional step of making an actual statement to Ukraine, asking Kiev to take action to remove the names of minors from Mirotvorets. 

As reported by RIA Novosti on December 7, 2022, UNICEF‚Äôs statement came following a UN Security Council Meeting on Tuesday in which Russian Permanent Representative to the UN Vasily Nebenzya spoke about the 327 children whose names have been added to the notorious database. Nebenzya asked what UNICEF was doing about this and what the organization‚Äôs position was on the publication of children‚Äôs personal data on the internet.

For years, young Faina and others targeted by Mirotvorets have appealed to international human rights groups such as The Red Cross, UNICEF and other but all they have received in response was silence, or platitudes.

The notorious Mirotvorets database discloses the private data of those it targets such as their home addresses, phone numbers and other personal information. It includes the names of more than 100,000 people including hundreds of children like Faina Savenkova, a 14-year-old from Lugansk who was added to the hitlist after speaking before a UN Security Council at the age of 12. The youngest child added to the list is only 9 years old.

Mirotvorets website calls their searchable database ‚ÄúPurgatory‚Äù. In twisted minds of Ukrainian nationalists anyone named on this kill list, whether they are children from Donbass, journalists who write about Donbass, or dissidents not in lockstep with Kiev, are said to already be in ‚Äúpurgatory‚Äù.

The very existence of such website and its endorsement and support by the government of Ukraine with eyes of the collective West conveniently looking elsewhere removes any questions about justification of Russian special military operation. Not only the Ukrainian regime has allowed this hit list to exist, but it integrated it into government structures as a part of Center for Countering Disinformation (CCD) of Ukraine‚Äôs Security and Defense Council. 

Taking international action against such a notorious directory endorsing murders and using neural recognition systems to help Nazis find potential victims was long due. However, it may be not a coincidence that UN structures finally took some action, and the core reason for it is likely not Nebenzya‚Äôs speech. 

‚ùóÔ∏èIt is quite possible that the story is more interesting. Looks like the founder of Mirotvorets Roman Zaitsev has some kind of disagreement with Vladimir Zelensky and in the end of November he did criticize the Ukrainian president calling him a liar with hands and wallet full of blood and virtually accusing him of treason.

Spiders in a jar are starting to eat each other. Maybe it‚Äôs not long before we see Zelensky himself on Mirotvorets list and that would be a pleasant sight. Still, while in Ukraine nationalists could be preparing to turn Zelensky into a sacrificial lamb, in the West he is still seen as the face of Ukraine and his words weigh much more.

‚ñ∂Ô∏è Why have Belarus avoided the fate of Ukraine and remained in the Russian world? 

That is not so hard to explain. The reason is simple ‚Äî because radical nationalists never came to power in Belarus. Ukrainian example also played a big role, most people in Belarus usually say: ‚ÄúThank you but we don‚Äôt want that experience‚Äù, referring to collapse of Ukrainian economy after 2014 and immense reduction of quality of life.

Besides, Belarus does not have the problem that Ukraine had. For its entire short history Ukraine has been internally split. West Ukraine is ridden with UPA* ideology and mentally closer to countries like Lithuania. It became a part of Ukraine only in times of WW2, just like the Baltic states, and these people probably really felt occupied and oppressed by Soviets. 

‚ñ∂Ô∏è Industrial Donbass has been pro-communist since tsarist times, while agricultural central Ukraine was more reactionary. Split of western Russia** in 1917-1918 between a dozen republics including German protectorate UNR shows the extent of local disagreements. 

Even the story of Bandera‚Äôs* infamous UPA* shows that the great split of Ukrainians continued even under communists. Now it was even more noticeable with UPA* being most popular in the West, while the East and the South giving roots to strong guerilla (‚Äúpartisan‚Äù) movement. 

After WW2 Stalin‚Äôs NKVD was hunting remains of UPA* and Bandera* followers. And again, in the West people weren‚Äôt that eager to give them up while in the East and in the South they were quickly rooted out. 

However, even strongest repressions did not help. In a couple decades Bandera veterans started returning home from labor camps and the ideology began spreading again. West Ukraine was pretty nationalistic and anti-Russian even in late USSR times, while East Ukraine was more pro-Union. 

There has never been such regional split in Belarus. The country is more or less uniform. In Ukraine radical nationalists came to prominence because people were sick of endless row of corrupt leaders. Nationalists didn‚Äôt help the country but at least they offered a culprit - Russia. 

Such thing still can happen in Belarus. Protests against Lukashenko had the scenario similar to Maidan with Western approval of fake president and broad support of social media. However, had they been successful, there would be a chance of radicals (less than 1% of Belarussians) coming to power instead of Lukashenko. 

* Fascist accomplices, ideology prohibited in Russia

** There was no state of Ukraine before it was created as German protectorate after the Treaty of Brest-Litovsk. 

‚ñ∂Ô∏è Technically those areas were just western governorates of the Russian Empire that have been conquered by external enemy. They were not different from other governorates. Historically term Ukraine (okraina - ukraina) was used to describe borderlands, it was a geographical concept first introduced by Poles that occupied the region for several centuries. That is why those areas are referred to as western Russia.

We are continuing mini-series of posts about typical features of fascism and their applicability to regime that has been in power in Ukraine since March 2014.

5Ô∏è‚É£ Fear of difference. 

‚ÄúThe first appeal of a fascist or prematurely fascist movement is an appeal against the intruders. Thus Ur-Fascism is racist by definition.‚Äù

National identity of modern Ukrainian nationalist has one sole ground ‚Äî proclaiming that they are not Russians. Persecution of Russian language and people identifying as Russians and their forced ukrainization is just a tip of an iceberg. Most other national minorities in Ukraine are in no better position, while remaining exceptions are used just as a token to show the Western society ‚Äî Ukrainians are no Nazis. 

Kiev regime openly proclaims superiority of Ukrainian nations, calls for genocide or ukrainization of Russian speakers, prohibits education of Russian people in Russian language. They fear Russian culture, they fear Russian language, they fear the real roots of Ukraine.

6Ô∏è‚É£ Appeal to social frustration. 

‚ÄúOne of the most typical features of the historical fascism was the appeal to a frustrated middle class, a class suffering from an economic crisis or feelings of political humiliation, and frightened by the pressure of lower social groups.‚Äù

Ukrainian society has different division with a few oligarchs, small middle class and large masses of people that cannot be classified as such. Small Ukrainian middle class does not actually share the state ideology, so the regime is instead appealing to poor categories of people and lures them with promises and pictures of happy life in European small towns. 

Kiev regime justifies hunger, deprivations, life below poverty line by talks about bright future of the country in European Union and while these talks have been going on for many years, Ukraine did not make a single real step towards achieving this dream they imposed over Ukrainian people.

7Ô∏è‚É£ The obsession with a plot. 

‚ÄúThus at the root of the Ur-Fascist psychology there is the obsession with a plot, possibly an international one. The followers must feel besieged.‚Äù

Naturally. All Ukrainian problems are not caused by incompetent government, greedy oligarchs and Western patrons draining every last bit of Ukrainian resources. Of course not. Kiev regime will tell you that 24 hours a day. All Ukrainian troubles are a result of Russian plot, it‚Äôs Putin‚Äôs mastermind plan to drive Ukraine into poverty. Why would Russians and Putin want it? See No. 3. No questions. 

8Ô∏è‚É£ The enemy is both strong and weak. 

‚ÄúBy a continuous shifting of rhetorical focus, the enemies are at the same time too strong and too weak.‚Äù

This narrative has been continuously spread not just by Ukraine but by the entire collective West both before and after 2022 and SMO. Of course, the main enemy is Russia. 

Russia is strong, it threatens poor Ukraine, give us money. At the same time it‚Äôs just a backward country without any serious weapons. 

Russian barbarians have invaded Ukraine and heroic Ukrainian army barely holds their defense against them, so please send them more weapons and money. Russian missile strikes are devastating Ukraine, and Zelensky urgently needs one trillion dollars to rebuild. At the same time, Russians have lost many hundred thousand soldiers and all their equipment and are now sending untrained children and old men armed with pitchforks.

Why are we sanctioning Russia when we depend on them for energy supply?

Sanctions against Russia were an attempt to cripple Russian military-industrial complex and create a hard time for Russian Armed Forces in Ukraine.

Both those objectives were not fulfilled. Russia has been weapon exporter for a long time and its military industrial complex was not dependent on import (and on external cash flow). 

Yes, some minor components were imported but nothing that couldn‚Äôt be replaced from local sources. Self-sufficient military industrial complex is an important aspect of a sovereign great power and Russia does have this aspect.

Russian Armed Forces in Ukraine don‚Äôt see any problem from sanctions. Soldiers are paid in rubles, their supplies come from local Russian sources. They have much more problems because of Western aid to Ukraine in form of military aid, mercenaries and NATO military advisors.

Sanctions against Russia resulted in some problems for Russian people. Fortunately, Russian government headed by Prime Minister Mishustin acted very smart and their brilliant and well-timed actions helped prevent economical crisis. Everything is fine in Russia. 

One last wave of the crisis (end of stock reserves of imported products and components that were available in Russia by February 2022) may hit Russia in a couple months, but the government had months to prepare for it, so I don‚Äôt think it will have any consequences.

Anyway, this sanction war has shown that both the West and Russia can survive without each other. However, people of both camps have problems because of trade termination. Not critical problems, but noticeable.

For Russia it‚Äôs more about absence of familiar brands, not about real shortage of something. No deficit of anything on consumer market.

For the West it‚Äôs increased energy costs that result in increased costs of anything. 

This is a long-term issue and now after North Stream explosions there is no easy way to bring energy costs down, even if Russia agrees to resume full supply. 

Ukrainian gas transit system is in a state of complete dilapidation and has been so for decades. Bringing it to modern safety standards would require investments comparable to costs of North Stream pipelines. 

And well, there will always be some political issue. By the way, despite Russian-Ukrainian military conflict those pipelines are still working. East European hawks say that they can meet all demands of Europe if needed.. in fact it‚Äôs a bit more complicated.

There is no simple solution to energy crisis in the West. The world will critically depend on fossil fuels for at least fifty more years. Nuclear option is available but electrical power can‚Äôt be used everywhere.

Eratosthenes‚Äô most famous accomplishment is his measurement of the circumference of Earth. He recorded the details of this measurement in a manuscript that is now lost, but his technique has been described by other Greek historians and writers.

Eratosthenes was fascinated with geography and planned to make a map of the entire world. He realized he needed to know the size of Earth. Obviously, one couldn‚Äôt walk all the way around to figure it out.

Eratosthenes had heard from travelers about a well in Syene (now Aswan, Egypt) with an interesting property: at noon on the summer solstice, which occurs about June 21 every year, the sun illuminated the entire bottom of this well, without casting any shadows, indicating that the sun was directly overhead. Eratosthenes then measured the angle of a shadow cast by a stick at noon on the summer solstice in Alexandria, and found it made an angle of about 7.2 degrees, or about 1/50 of a complete circle.

He realized that if he knew the distance from Alexandria to Syene, he could easily calculate the circumference of Earth. But in those days it was extremely difficult to determine distance with any accuracy. Some distances between cities were measured by the time it took a camel caravan to travel from one city to the other. But camels have a tendency to wander and to walk at varying speeds. So Eratosthenes hired bematists, professional surveyors trained to walk with equal length steps. They found that Syene lies about 5000 stadia from Alexandria.

Eratosthenes then used this to calculate the circumference of the Earth to be about 250,000 stadia. Modern scholars disagree about the length of the stadium used by Eratosthenes. Values between 500 and about 600 feet have been suggested, putting Eratosthenes‚Äô calculated circumference between about 24,000 miles and about 29,000 miles. The Earth is now known to measure about 24,900 miles around the equator, slightly less around the poles.

Eratosthenes had made the assumption that the sun was so far away that its rays were essentially parallel, that Alexandria is due north of Syene, and that Syene is exactly on the tropic of cancer. While not exactly correct, these assumptions are good enough to make a quite accurate measurement using Eratosthenes‚Äô method. His basic method is sound, and is even used by schoolchildren around the world today.
